 The `debounce` function is used to prevent a function from being called too often by providing a "cooldown" period in which the function will only be executed once, regardless of how many times it's called.
```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay = 500) {
  let timer = 0;
  return function(...args) {
    if (timer) {
      clearTimeout(timer);
    }
    timer = window.setTimeout(() => {
      fn(...args);
      timer = 0;
    }, delay);
  };
}

const typeInput = debounce(function(event) {
  console.log(event.target.value);
}, 500);

document.getElementById("input").addEventListener("input", typeInput);
```

In this example, the `debounce` function is used with the `input` event on an `<input>`, so it will only log the value of the input after 500ms of inactivity. This prevents the console from being flooded with log messages while the user is typing.
